[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(18) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And he set . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and he made seventy thousand of them bearers of burdens, and eighty thousand hewers in the mountains.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This exactly agrees with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 5:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And three thousand and six hundred overseers.—The same number was given in 2Chronicles 2:2. In 1Kings 5:16 we read of 3,300 officers. In the Hebrew, three (shālôsh) and six (shêsh) might easily be confused; our reading appears right. The chronicler omits all notice of the levy of 30,000 Israelites, which the parallel passage records (1Kings 5:13-14); whether by an oversight, or from disapproval, we cannot say. Adding that number to the 70,000 and 80,000 other labourers, we get a grand total of 180,000, which gives a company of 50 for each of the 3,600 overseers.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And three thousand and six hundred overseers.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The same number was given in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 2:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". In ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 5:16",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " we read of 3,300 officers. In the Hebrew, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "three",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "shālôsh",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "six",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "shêsh",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") might easily be confused; our reading appears right. The chronicler omits all notice of the levy of 30,000 Israelites, which the parallel passage records (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 5:13-14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "); whether by an oversight, or from disapproval, we cannot say. Adding that number to the 70,000 and 80,000 other labourers, we get a grand total of 180,000, which gives a company of 50 for each of the 3,600 overseers.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Overseers.—Heb. mĕnaççĕhîm. Only here and in 2Chronicles 2:2 supra, and 2Chronicles 34:13. It is the plural of a participle which occurs only in the titles of the Psalms (including Habakkuk 3:19), while the verb is read only in Chronicles and Ezra 3:8-9. (See Note on 1Chronicles 15:21.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Overseers.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Heb. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "mĕnaççĕhîm.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " Only here and in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 2:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "supra,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 34:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". It is the plural of a participle which occurs only in the titles of the Psalms (including ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Habakkuk 3:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), while the verb is read only in Chronicles and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezra 3:8-9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". (See Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 15:21",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To set the people a work—i.e., on work or a-working. (Comp. “I go a-fishing,” John 21:3.) Literally, to make the people work.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "To set the people a work",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "on work",
            "children": []
